WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.680
Hi everybody, welcome to the Data Science Hangout.

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:14.080
If you're joining for the first time, I'm Rachel, and it's great to meet you.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:18.440
If you've been here before, you've heard this feel a bunch of times before.

00:00:18.440 --> 00:00:23.320
But if this is your first Hangout, this is an open space for the whole data science community

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:28.940
to connect and chat about data science leadership, questions you're facing, and what's really

00:00:28.940 --> 00:00:31.660
going on in the world of data science.

00:00:31.660 --> 00:00:36.580
So the sessions are recorded and shared to the rstudio YouTube, as well as the Data Science

00:00:36.580 --> 00:00:37.580
Hangout site.

00:00:37.580 --> 00:00:41.619
So you can always go back and rewatch and find helpful resources too.

00:00:41.619 --> 00:00:47.340
I'll say it up front as well, because I always forget, we do have a LinkedIn group as well

00:00:47.340 --> 00:00:48.340
for the Hangout.

00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:53.500
So if you ever want to connect with people there or continue a certain discussion, you

00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:54.500
can use that too.

00:00:55.340 --> 00:00:59.060
I'll put it into the chat in just a moment.

00:00:59.060 --> 00:01:04.660
We always want to create spaces where everybody can participate and we can hear from everyone.

00:01:04.660 --> 00:01:07.580
So there's three ways that you can ask questions today.

00:01:07.580 --> 00:01:09.580
All this is audience led.

00:01:09.580 --> 00:01:12.599
You can jump in by raising your hand on Zoom.

00:01:12.599 --> 00:01:15.379
You can put questions into the Zoom chat.

00:01:15.379 --> 00:01:19.940
And feel free to just put a little star next to it if you want me to read it out loud.

00:01:19.940 --> 00:01:24.580
Or I could just call on you to introduce yourself and add some context.

00:01:24.580 --> 00:01:29.379
And then also we have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously too.

00:01:29.379 --> 00:01:31.620
And I see Tyler just shared that in the chat.

00:01:31.620 --> 00:01:32.620
Thank you.

00:01:32.620 --> 00:01:38.059
I like to reiterate, we love to hear from everyone, regardless of your level of experience

00:01:38.059 --> 00:01:41.580
or the area of work as well.

00:01:41.580 --> 00:01:46.019
But with all that, today I'm so happy to be joined by my co-host.

00:01:46.019 --> 00:01:53.220
And I'll say, so excited that I even announced on Twitter a day ahead that I thought yesterday

00:01:53.220 --> 00:01:54.220
was Thursday.

00:01:54.220 --> 00:01:59.260
But so excited to be joined by my co-host for today, Tanya Casciarelli.

00:01:59.260 --> 00:02:03.099
Tanya is CEO and founder of TCV Analytics.

00:02:03.099 --> 00:02:06.820
And Tanya, I'd like to kick these off with just having you introduce yourself and sharing

00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:09.220
a little bit about the work that you do.

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:10.220
Sure.

00:02:10.220 --> 00:02:11.220
Yeah.

00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:12.220
Yeah.

00:02:12.220 --> 00:02:13.220
I got nervous.

00:02:13.220 --> 00:02:15.380
I was like, oh no, is it Wednesday instead of Thursday?

00:02:15.740 --> 00:02:20.419
Yeah, it's been one of those weeks.

00:02:20.419 --> 00:02:21.419
I'm Tanya.

00:02:21.419 --> 00:02:29.619
I, let's say the short version, I got my career started, I dual majored in computer science

00:02:29.619 --> 00:02:30.619
and biology.

00:02:30.619 --> 00:02:32.619
So I started in the bioinformatics world.

00:02:32.619 --> 00:02:38.300
So probably unsurprisingly, that's how I got started using R.

00:02:38.300 --> 00:02:41.300
It was about 2005 or so, believe it or not.

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:47.220
And I was working at a children's hospital informatics program for a bunch of really

00:02:47.220 --> 00:02:50.220
smart PhDs and had no clue what R is.

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:55.539
He told me, go home this summer and read about R. So I actually printed like the entirety

00:02:55.539 --> 00:03:00.460
of the CRAN documentation and took it home and thought, oh man, this is like really,

00:03:00.460 --> 00:03:05.419
I thought it was just, I was in over my head, but yeah, I had some really great mentors

00:03:05.419 --> 00:03:06.940
and learned a lot.

00:03:06.940 --> 00:03:12.820
And then I worked in biotech for a few years, a bunch of startups, and then I did some non

00:03:12.820 --> 00:03:19.500
healthcare stuff, a telecom startup, found myself back in healthcare at Biogen, which

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:23.660
is a big, my first big company that I worked at and always knew I wanted to consult and

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:24.940
kind of do stuff on the side.

00:03:24.940 --> 00:03:29.899
So I was doing that and only lasted there nine months, big company, just like wasn't

00:03:29.899 --> 00:03:35.500
for me, even though I learned a lot and had a great time, met a lot of cool people.

00:03:35.500 --> 00:03:39.100
And then I started TCB analytics in 2015 or so.

00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:48.539
And we have clients kind of all industries, pharma, we do, we work with financial trading

00:03:48.539 --> 00:03:49.539
companies.

00:03:49.539 --> 00:03:53.419
We worked with the department of defense and we did some pretty cool AI machine learning

00:03:53.419 --> 00:03:55.839
stuff for the army.

00:03:55.839 --> 00:03:59.619
So really all over the map and just having fun because we get to kind of pick and choose

00:03:59.619 --> 00:04:02.100
our projects and I get to work with friends.

00:04:02.100 --> 00:04:05.460
So that was a short, short answer.

00:04:05.460 --> 00:04:06.460
That's awesome.

00:04:06.460 --> 00:04:11.460
While we're waiting for questions to come in from everyone, I'm curious, what's something

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:16.380
you're most excited about in data science in the next year or so?

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:20.579
Yeah, I, you know, I started, I was thinking about like what tools and stuff are exciting,

00:04:20.579 --> 00:04:23.140
but I don't even think it's tooling or anything like that.

00:04:23.140 --> 00:04:28.459
It's it's really that it's becoming more widespread and known and I feel like it's getting evangelized

00:04:28.459 --> 00:04:33.660
more and the more people I talk to people, a lot of you have probably had this experience

00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:35.220
before, like what the heck is data science?

00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:37.220
I have no idea what you're talking about.

00:04:37.220 --> 00:04:40.660
And usually I use the sports example because everyone kind of knows the movie money ball

00:04:40.660 --> 00:04:43.100
and fantasy sports.

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:47.260
And I just think people are starting to get it more.

00:04:47.260 --> 00:04:49.779
And obviously that's good for us and helpful for us.

00:04:49.779 --> 00:04:54.700
So it's simple answer, but yeah, I think I'm just excited that more and more people are

00:04:54.700 --> 00:04:55.820
just getting it.

00:04:55.820 --> 00:05:01.980
Like I thought years ago that CEOs at every company should be familiar enough with data

00:05:01.980 --> 00:05:06.940
and the basics of data analysis, the same way that they were expected to be familiar

00:05:06.940 --> 00:05:09.820
with email, like 30 years ago, everyone started using email.

00:05:09.820 --> 00:05:11.980
I think data is getting to that same point.

00:05:11.980 --> 00:05:12.980
Definitely.

00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:17.380
I see Libby, you asked the question in the chat, if you want to jump in.

00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:18.380
Sure.

00:05:18.380 --> 00:05:24.700
I was wondering what about your experience made you decide that the big company was not

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:25.700
the right one for you?

00:05:25.700 --> 00:05:31.220
Whether that was like wanting a bigger variety of projects or there were IT barriers or different

00:05:31.220 --> 00:05:32.220
stuff like that.

00:05:32.220 --> 00:05:33.220
Yeah.

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:38.700
I think the pace at which things moved, now at the time I was very burnt out from working

00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:39.700
at startups.

00:05:39.700 --> 00:05:43.940
So I kind of liked like breathing a little bit.

00:05:43.940 --> 00:05:50.299
And I think just a lot of politics to have to go through, trying to do seemingly simple

00:05:50.299 --> 00:05:52.019
tasks, it just was like a lot of bureaucracy.

00:05:52.019 --> 00:05:56.779
So you kind of felt like you had your hands tied in a lot of situations.

00:05:56.779 --> 00:06:01.540
That said, there were really good parts about it too, just learning how to navigate those

00:06:01.540 --> 00:06:04.739
big companies and the people that I met.

00:06:04.739 --> 00:06:09.059
But yeah, I'd say it was probably just, I felt like I couldn't really get much done

00:06:09.059 --> 00:06:13.420
or push the needle in certain ways that I could in a startup.

00:06:13.420 --> 00:06:14.420
Yeah.

00:06:14.420 --> 00:06:17.420
Lots of red tape, exactly.

00:06:18.420 --> 00:06:22.220
I see, Connor, you just asked a question as well, if you want to jump in next.

00:06:22.220 --> 00:06:23.980
Hi, Tanya.

00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:27.140
I work here at RStudio with our consulting customers.

00:06:27.140 --> 00:06:32.100
So I would love to understand what you view as like the biggest challenges for data analytics

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:38.100
consulting in 2022 or just in general.

00:06:38.100 --> 00:06:39.100
Biggest challenges.

00:06:39.100 --> 00:06:40.859
It's always people.

00:06:40.859 --> 00:06:43.019
It's never R, it does everything.

00:06:43.420 --> 00:06:50.380
I can make R and Shiny do anything, but it comes down to, I think, I could tell when

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:52.339
a client kind of knows exactly what they want.

00:06:52.339 --> 00:06:56.540
And most of our prospects and customers come to us saying, we know we need this.

00:06:56.540 --> 00:06:57.540
We love Shiny.

00:06:57.540 --> 00:07:00.700
We want to do things with Shiny and data.

00:07:00.700 --> 00:07:05.140
But I think the hardest part is getting people to understand why they're doing what they're

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:06.140
doing.

00:07:06.140 --> 00:07:11.339
There's so many times where people just want to put all the data into a data lake or let's

00:07:11.380 --> 00:07:15.100
join all these tables and I'm like, why?

00:07:15.100 --> 00:07:19.459
So I'm always asking, well, what questions are you trying to answer?

00:07:19.459 --> 00:07:22.459
And more importantly, what action will be taken?

00:07:22.459 --> 00:07:27.059
And this sounds probably like a trope to everyone on this call, but it's amazing how many people

00:07:27.059 --> 00:07:32.100
and clients just, they want to check a box or they want to do the fun data thing, but

00:07:32.100 --> 00:07:38.779
they don't have any valuable business reasons for doing it.

00:07:38.779 --> 00:07:40.339
So that's a hard thing.

00:07:40.339 --> 00:07:42.859
And then another thing, it's always scoping.

00:07:42.859 --> 00:07:48.220
I feel like with data products, it's much different from a web application because there's

00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:50.980
so many possibilities.

00:07:50.980 --> 00:07:54.660
As we're building things, we constantly run into situations and scenarios we could not

00:07:54.660 --> 00:07:57.459
have predicted until we start building it.

00:07:57.459 --> 00:08:01.779
So that's always tough, but we try to mitigate that by doing either retainer-based contracts

00:08:01.779 --> 00:08:08.700
or being really conservative with the fixed price and really scoping it out well.

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:09.700
Thank you.

00:08:10.059 --> 00:08:11.059
Yeah.

00:08:11.059 --> 00:08:12.059
And I noticed someone noticed my turntables.

00:08:12.059 --> 00:08:17.540
I used to DJ in college back when I was still cool in Boston, and I actually, I busted them

00:08:17.540 --> 00:08:18.899
back out during the pandemic.

00:08:18.899 --> 00:08:22.459
So that's what that is.

00:08:22.459 --> 00:08:27.540
I think you may be the third data science leader slash DJ that we have.

00:08:27.540 --> 00:08:28.540
Really?

00:08:28.540 --> 00:08:29.540
Oh, who are the other?

00:08:29.540 --> 00:08:30.540
I got to know who the other ones are.

00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:32.460
Tanya, it's funny.

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:34.500
This is Javier.

00:08:34.500 --> 00:08:38.140
There's another person here who lives in Southern California, Sep.

00:08:38.140 --> 00:08:41.979
I don't know if he's on this meetup today.

00:08:41.979 --> 00:08:45.619
He's involved with the SoCalR users group, but we've known each other for a few years

00:08:45.619 --> 00:08:48.219
and only this year realized we were both DJs.

00:08:48.219 --> 00:08:52.179
So we got together a few months ago and had a little garage DJ session.

00:08:52.179 --> 00:08:53.179
It was fun.

00:08:53.179 --> 00:08:54.179
Oh, that's awesome.

00:08:54.179 --> 00:08:57.820
Well, if you're down in Florida, you'll have to let me know.

00:08:57.820 --> 00:08:58.820
Yeah.

00:08:58.820 --> 00:09:01.500
Tanya, I did have a quick question for you.

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:05.700
You talked about making sure sort of your statement of works are very clear and concise

00:09:05.859 --> 00:09:09.179
and that, you know, you try and price project based.

00:09:09.179 --> 00:09:14.059
How do you, I don't think the problem is data science related necessarily, but how do you

00:09:14.059 --> 00:09:17.460
manage scope creep?

00:09:17.460 --> 00:09:18.460
It's tough.

00:09:18.460 --> 00:09:19.460
Yeah.

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:24.659
Cause I mean, there's, there's times where you give a little and, you know, you know,

00:09:24.659 --> 00:09:28.659
show of good faith where things are actually easy to do and you do it as like, all right,

00:09:28.659 --> 00:09:31.539
like we'll do this one thing, but then that can be a slippery slope and they think that

00:09:31.539 --> 00:09:33.140
now we can ask for all the things.

00:09:33.140 --> 00:09:40.580
So it comes down to, I think if you can itemize everything, you know, whether it's in GitHub

00:09:40.580 --> 00:09:46.140
issues or just JIRA anywhere, and then really prioritize that list.

00:09:46.140 --> 00:09:50.260
So I find it's really hard to do in a phase one because you're learning so much.

00:09:50.260 --> 00:09:55.419
So we try to, we try to estimate in like an exploratory sometimes one month long even

00:09:55.419 --> 00:09:57.739
to properly scope.

00:09:57.739 --> 00:10:01.780
And that always, you know, it's never perfect, but I find for the second phase, and we just

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:03.539
did this with a project.

00:10:03.539 --> 00:10:06.340
We know a lot more and they started asking for so many things.

00:10:06.340 --> 00:10:11.539
We kept a backlog and then we have our consultants go in and estimate.

00:10:11.539 --> 00:10:16.500
And we always pretty much, I wouldn't say double, but we add some padding onto that

00:10:16.500 --> 00:10:17.940
for uncertainties.

00:10:17.940 --> 00:10:20.940
And then you just throw it back to the client and say, look, you could purchase, you know,

00:10:20.940 --> 00:10:23.979
block of hours, 50 hours, a hundred hours, but here's the list.

00:10:23.979 --> 00:10:27.780
And now you put the onus on them to prioritize and say, okay, well, we definitely want this

00:10:27.780 --> 00:10:28.940
and this.

00:10:29.099 --> 00:10:33.059
And then even on top of that, I typically recommend another block of miscellaneous hours

00:10:33.059 --> 00:10:35.659
for like unknowns that come up.

00:10:35.659 --> 00:10:39.419
And that allows you to at least like quantify it because it becomes very like hand wavy

00:10:39.419 --> 00:10:41.820
if you don't have that.

00:10:41.820 --> 00:10:45.700
And if you can't back it into the money or the cost, it's tough.

00:10:45.700 --> 00:10:48.460
So I find fixed price, it can go either way.

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:53.140
It can really bite you if it's not scoped well, or you can actually make some good margins

00:10:53.140 --> 00:10:54.580
on it.

00:10:54.580 --> 00:10:59.020
So we try to balance that with every project and I've just learned more and more over the

00:10:59.020 --> 00:11:00.020
years of doing it.

00:11:00.020 --> 00:11:03.940
It really just has taken a lot of trial and error and I've messed up for sure and learned

00:11:03.940 --> 00:11:08.859
lessons from it.

00:11:08.859 --> 00:11:09.859
Thank you.

00:11:09.859 --> 00:11:10.859
I know.

00:11:10.859 --> 00:11:15.940
And one of the answers just before this, you said like the hardest thing is people and

00:11:15.940 --> 00:11:19.619
like having those conversations with people and they just want to put a bunch of data

00:11:19.619 --> 00:11:21.659
into a data lake.

00:11:21.739 --> 00:11:24.940
How do you approach those conversations?

00:11:24.940 --> 00:11:26.940
Yeah.

00:11:26.940 --> 00:11:33.659
So one thing I like to do is, again, I always say, I try to say like what are people going

00:11:33.659 --> 00:11:34.659
to pay for?

00:11:34.659 --> 00:11:38.700
Like what are you building that your clients actually will put money towards?

00:11:38.700 --> 00:11:41.619
Number two is, again, what will they do with this information?

00:11:41.619 --> 00:11:42.900
Can they take action from it?

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:47.260
An example I can think of is like when you log into E-Trade or Vanguard and you look

00:11:47.260 --> 00:11:54.099
at your stocks and it says that you've got a, you know, 100% gain on this stock, well,

00:11:54.099 --> 00:11:55.099
what is that?

00:11:55.099 --> 00:11:56.099
What do I want to do about that?

00:11:56.099 --> 00:11:57.099
I want to sell it.

00:11:57.099 --> 00:11:58.340
So typically there's a sell button like right there.

00:11:58.340 --> 00:12:02.299
You never have to like look and browse through five more pages to get to the sell button.

00:12:02.299 --> 00:12:07.659
Oh, Porkchop appeared.

00:12:07.659 --> 00:12:13.940
So I think that's a couple of questions I try to ask consistently is, you know, what

00:12:13.940 --> 00:12:17.580
will your clients pay for and what decisions are they trying to make?

00:12:17.580 --> 00:12:22.020
And then I'll do that same exercise with the people that are really like driving product

00:12:22.020 --> 00:12:24.700
management or the data analysis.

00:12:24.700 --> 00:12:30.340
So we'll actually sit with a mock-up, Balsamiq or, you know, name your favorite mock-up tool

00:12:30.340 --> 00:12:31.820
and we'll talk through it and we'll lay it out.

00:12:31.820 --> 00:12:35.179
And it's amazing the questions that come up and once people start thinking about it and

00:12:35.179 --> 00:12:39.140
seeing it and they think, oh yeah, actually we need a filter here because I didn't think

00:12:39.140 --> 00:12:41.460
that, you know, the date range would matter.

00:12:42.020 --> 00:12:46.020
We need a minimum threshold filter because we have so few data points in this state.

00:12:46.659 --> 00:12:50.099
But those are things that I learned as I build things in Shiny, to be honest.

00:12:51.299 --> 00:12:52.580
Just building it and showing it.

00:12:54.020 --> 00:12:54.520
Yeah.

00:12:56.020 --> 00:12:56.520
That's great.

00:12:57.140 --> 00:13:01.140
Darren, I see you have kind of a follow-up to this question as well.

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:02.099
You want to jump in?

00:13:02.099 --> 00:13:02.979
Yeah, thanks, Rachel.

00:13:03.700 --> 00:13:09.700
Yeah, Javier, you kind of asked my question and I had a follow-up to that based on Tanya's

00:13:09.700 --> 00:13:10.179
response.

00:13:10.179 --> 00:13:16.179
So I've had a lot of experiences when working with other clients in previous jobs where

00:13:16.179 --> 00:13:22.739
they tell me I know what I want, I know what I don't want, but I don't know what I want.

00:13:22.739 --> 00:13:27.780
And so I'm kind of curious if you had those similar experiences and how you manage those

00:13:28.419 --> 00:13:31.940
expectations while also delivering a product that they don't really know what they want.

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:38.580
Yeah, that's like kind of where the art comes in, I think, is and also getting the right

00:13:38.580 --> 00:13:40.900
people involved on the client side.

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:46.580
So if there's a subject matter expert, I always try to work with them.

00:13:46.580 --> 00:13:52.179
Or if there's someone that I know is a decision maker, because, yeah, it can be tough.

00:13:53.780 --> 00:13:55.299
Trying to think of another example.

00:13:59.619 --> 00:14:03.299
I think it's important not to also rush to building something.

00:14:03.299 --> 00:14:06.340
There's definitely rapid prototyping, but then there's like, well, let's actually take

00:14:06.340 --> 00:14:07.140
a minute and think.

00:14:07.780 --> 00:14:12.099
I try to list out all the most common questions and use cases and then also understand who

00:14:12.099 --> 00:14:13.380
are the end users.

00:14:13.380 --> 00:14:19.140
Because if this is a CMO using it versus a data analyst, one's going to be a very exploratory

00:14:19.140 --> 00:14:22.099
design or dashboard, and another one's going to be explanatory.

00:14:22.099 --> 00:14:25.940
Very simple, high-level KPIs, maybe some drill downs, right?

00:14:27.859 --> 00:14:28.659
So yeah, it's tough.

00:14:28.659 --> 00:14:32.979
It really comes back to having those conversations kind of repeatedly over and over until it

00:14:32.979 --> 00:14:33.700
starts to click.

00:14:34.340 --> 00:14:37.299
But it's one of the hardest things we have to deal with.

00:14:38.260 --> 00:14:42.260
But then again, I get clients that come in and they know, and they start building it,

00:14:42.260 --> 00:14:43.460
and they're like, this is great.

00:14:45.299 --> 00:14:46.580
I hope that answers the question.

00:14:46.580 --> 00:14:50.340
But yeah, it's not an easy thing to navigate, for sure.

00:14:50.900 --> 00:14:53.700
That's why I like the Shiny prototyping, actually.

00:14:53.700 --> 00:14:58.580
Because you can kind of iterate until they say, OK, this is right, versus like a full

00:14:58.580 --> 00:15:00.179
software build that could take months.

00:15:01.140 --> 00:15:07.140
And then you're kind of stuck with this big React thing and custom D3, and it's not the

00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:07.539
right thing.

00:15:12.340 --> 00:15:17.780
See, Javier, you're commenting maybe to another question in the chat, too.

00:15:18.500 --> 00:15:20.260
But Mark, I see you have a question there as well.

00:15:20.260 --> 00:15:20.979
Do you want to jump in?

00:15:23.539 --> 00:15:24.020
Yeah, sure.

00:15:24.020 --> 00:15:24.659
Can you guys hear me?

00:15:25.940 --> 00:15:26.580
Yep.

00:15:26.580 --> 00:15:26.979
OK.

00:15:26.979 --> 00:15:28.820
Sorry, my sound's been funky.

00:15:28.820 --> 00:15:31.219
Yeah, it was a follow-up to Darren's question.

00:15:33.059 --> 00:15:35.299
And I'm thinking from my own experience.

00:15:35.299 --> 00:15:38.900
I don't have external clients.

00:15:38.900 --> 00:15:40.820
It's all internal for the company I work for.

00:15:40.820 --> 00:15:49.380
But have you ever had a scenario where up front your client is very clear about what

00:15:49.380 --> 00:15:53.780
it is that they want, the inputs and outputs, and it's very well-defined?

00:15:53.859 --> 00:15:59.140
And then you deliver that some time later, and then all of a sudden things have changed,

00:15:59.140 --> 00:16:01.940
and now they're wanting something else.

00:16:01.940 --> 00:16:04.659
And then if so, how do you deal with that scenario?

00:16:06.500 --> 00:16:06.979
Yeah.

00:16:06.979 --> 00:16:13.460
And I see Javier's note said luckily over seven years, probably still only two or so

00:16:13.460 --> 00:16:15.059
also nightmare scenarios like that.

00:16:16.659 --> 00:16:20.900
But it seemed like they were very clear up front on what they wanted.

00:16:20.900 --> 00:16:22.979
It turns out that they were not.

00:16:24.179 --> 00:16:25.859
And it's a tough situation.

00:16:26.739 --> 00:16:30.020
And also when you're dealing with people or contractors, things happen in life.

00:16:30.020 --> 00:16:35.059
And we've had on one occasion, a contractor just have to go pursue a full-time job in

00:16:35.059 --> 00:16:35.940
the middle of a project.

00:16:35.940 --> 00:16:38.659
So luckily, you have a bench to handle things like that.

00:16:38.659 --> 00:16:49.219
But yeah, I'd say it really comes down to I keep revisiting the SOW and the scope and

00:16:49.219 --> 00:16:51.299
saying I literally will map it out.

00:16:51.299 --> 00:16:53.140
Here's what we said the deliverable was.

00:16:53.140 --> 00:16:54.099
Here's what we did.

00:16:54.099 --> 00:16:54.979
Here's a deliverable.

00:16:54.979 --> 00:16:55.700
Here's what we did.

00:16:56.260 --> 00:16:58.099
Here are some things we even did that were out of scope.

00:16:59.380 --> 00:17:05.140
So hopefully, you can get to a point where you can justify the end phase by using that

00:17:05.140 --> 00:17:06.099
SOW.

00:17:06.099 --> 00:17:10.180
Now, the problem is that we've had is it actually wasn't that clear.

00:17:10.180 --> 00:17:12.099
SOW is very high level and vague.

00:17:13.060 --> 00:17:17.459
So then you run into a scenario where you're doing a whole bunch of extra work, and you're

00:17:17.459 --> 00:17:20.819
cutting into margins, and that sucks.

00:17:20.819 --> 00:17:26.420
So you try to wrap it up as quickly as possible with the minimum viable product or solution,

00:17:26.420 --> 00:17:28.260
and then go on to the next phase.

00:17:28.260 --> 00:17:34.979
And honestly, try to make up that cash in the next phase, because there's a lot of work

00:17:34.979 --> 00:17:35.699
that was done.

00:17:35.699 --> 00:17:37.699
And SOW, yeah, statement of work.

00:17:39.619 --> 00:17:44.339
But yeah, to try to mitigate that, you can always, if they're happy with the end goal,

00:17:44.339 --> 00:17:47.300
regardless of how it went, they're going to pay you for more work.

00:17:47.619 --> 00:17:52.339
You can, I always try to make it up a little bit in the second phase by either over-delivering

00:17:52.339 --> 00:17:56.900
on things or just adding in a few more low-hanging fruit things we know we can do.

00:17:57.540 --> 00:17:58.979
But that is highly valuable.

00:17:58.979 --> 00:18:05.699
Like speed, some optimizations, let's parallelize this thing and give them a 10x factor speed

00:18:05.699 --> 00:18:06.020
boost.

00:18:06.020 --> 00:18:09.619
And that's hugely valuable for them, even if it doesn't take us a long time.

00:18:10.339 --> 00:18:13.060
Because I always try to tell people, they're paying for your experience.

00:18:13.060 --> 00:18:19.459
Just because it takes you a couple of days, it would take their team maybe never, or a

00:18:19.459 --> 00:18:21.380
few weeks or months.

00:18:21.380 --> 00:18:25.699
So always value-based price as much as possible and not just your time.

00:18:25.699 --> 00:18:29.140
Because you've been learning, we've been learning this stuff and researching and doing

00:18:29.140 --> 00:18:30.500
it for years and years and years, right?

00:18:30.500 --> 00:18:31.459
That's what they're paying for.

00:18:33.300 --> 00:18:36.420
So that might be a long-winded question, or sorry, answer.

00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:40.579
The other thing I'll mention is, in the beginning, we realized one mistake was that the whole

00:18:40.579 --> 00:18:47.540
project was scoped by the data analysts, the users of the tool, and not the engineers.

00:18:47.540 --> 00:18:50.180
And it turned into much more of a software engineering problem.

00:18:51.300 --> 00:18:56.180
So there's a lot of complexity behind this tool that the analysts were using that they

00:18:56.180 --> 00:18:56.660
didn't see.

00:18:56.660 --> 00:18:58.339
It was like a magic black box to them.

00:18:59.219 --> 00:19:04.739
So next time, I'd probably make sure that I pull in an engineer and understand more of

00:19:04.739 --> 00:19:09.060
the technical requirements of the thing we were essentially rebuilding.

00:19:11.300 --> 00:19:12.260
Yeah, that makes sense.

00:19:14.339 --> 00:19:14.900
Yeah, thanks.

00:19:14.900 --> 00:19:15.459
Sorry, Mark.

00:19:15.459 --> 00:19:16.579
Didn't mean to jump in on you.

00:19:18.739 --> 00:19:22.819
Edgar, I see you also put a question into the chat if you want to jump in next.

00:19:22.819 --> 00:19:23.540
Oh, absolutely.

00:19:23.540 --> 00:19:25.380
And I apologize for the typo.

00:19:25.380 --> 00:19:32.500
But I've struggled over time to get a good sense of developing a burndown rate so that

00:19:32.500 --> 00:19:38.020
I know when to stop working on what I'm working because it's getting too big in size or way

00:19:38.020 --> 00:19:38.579
out of scope.

00:19:39.300 --> 00:19:41.380
Do you have any wisdom there to share?

00:19:42.979 --> 00:19:45.939
Are you typically doing like hourly?

00:19:45.939 --> 00:19:46.819
Is it a fixed price?

00:19:48.420 --> 00:19:48.819
No, no.

00:19:49.380 --> 00:19:51.380
Well, I should kind of give a little background.

00:19:51.380 --> 00:19:53.939
I work for internal stakeholders, right?

00:19:53.939 --> 00:19:59.459
So it's more so if we think about having 2,000 hours available of people.

00:20:00.500 --> 00:20:04.819
And then at some point, you're trading off with other projects or other stakeholders

00:20:04.819 --> 00:20:10.900
because this one project, it's just turning into a Frankenstein or like, you know, how

00:20:10.900 --> 00:20:14.579
to kind of stop and say, you know, get back to the end of the line now.

00:20:15.540 --> 00:20:16.260
It turns up.

00:20:17.380 --> 00:20:20.260
Yeah, it's tough.

00:20:20.260 --> 00:20:26.020
I, again, try to always get to an end phase that everyone's agreed upon.

00:20:26.020 --> 00:20:28.500
Like, OK, we're done with this phase.

00:20:28.500 --> 00:20:34.260
Let's stop here because we delivered X, Y, and Z, which we agreed upon.

00:20:34.260 --> 00:20:36.900
And now there's a bunch of extra things that are creeping in.

00:20:36.900 --> 00:20:41.380
And let's properly size those and estimate and start a new phase.

00:20:41.380 --> 00:20:45.939
And if you feel like, well, we need to charge more this time around, or we need to pull

00:20:45.939 --> 00:20:49.780
in different people, or sometimes, you know, if we know we don't need a senior statistician,

00:20:49.780 --> 00:20:53.380
for example, PhD, we could charge.

00:20:53.380 --> 00:20:56.500
We charge a lower hourly rate, of course, for like a data analyst.

00:20:57.459 --> 00:21:01.219
Or if there's no like, you know, crazy statistics or machine learning needed.

00:21:02.020 --> 00:21:06.099
So that's one thing we've done to reduce cost is we realize, oh, we don't need like, you

00:21:06.099 --> 00:21:08.339
know, our highest rate card price.

00:21:08.339 --> 00:21:12.500
We can pull in someone else, but still, you know, still keep the charges the way it is.

00:21:13.939 --> 00:21:17.219
So, you know, but it all comes down, again, I think, to value base.

00:21:17.219 --> 00:21:23.859
Like, you know, if you can say, look, we've delivered, or if you can actually ask the

00:21:23.859 --> 00:21:27.300
client how much budget they have, that's always an ideal scenario.

00:21:27.380 --> 00:21:31.699
Because that means that they have budget, meaning it's important.

00:21:33.380 --> 00:21:36.819
It also gives you an idea for what they value it to be.

00:21:36.819 --> 00:21:40.979
And we've heard budgets that are sometimes way under what we can accommodate.

00:21:40.979 --> 00:21:43.140
And we just say, you know, that's not for us.

00:21:43.859 --> 00:21:46.420
Sometimes they're much higher, and then we'll give them options.

00:21:46.420 --> 00:21:47.300
We'll give them tiers.

00:21:47.300 --> 00:21:49.380
Like, here's a bottom tier.

00:21:49.380 --> 00:21:52.180
It's very basic, middle, highest.

00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:56.180
And the highest we usually make kind of ridiculous and hope they don't pick it.

00:21:56.180 --> 00:21:57.380
Sometimes they do, right?

00:21:57.380 --> 00:21:58.660
They want all the bells and whistles.

00:21:58.660 --> 00:22:00.900
And we say, okay, we got to, like, size up the team a bit.

00:22:01.619 --> 00:22:02.020
Got it.

00:22:02.020 --> 00:22:06.260
I see I can draw a parallel to what we still use, which is by when you need it done.

00:22:06.260 --> 00:22:10.739
Like, when do you present to your VP or your, you know, most senior leader?

00:22:10.739 --> 00:22:16.020
And that's, like, past that date, we don't continue working kind of thing.

00:22:16.020 --> 00:22:20.579
So just having a hard deadline where it's budgetary or time-driven.

00:22:20.579 --> 00:22:21.380
Thanks.

00:22:21.380 --> 00:22:22.420
Yep, no problem.

00:22:23.300 --> 00:22:26.099
I see there's a few questions on Slido as well.

00:22:26.099 --> 00:22:30.900
And one was, how do you share your apps with your clients so they're hidden from your other

00:22:30.900 --> 00:22:31.699
clients?

00:22:31.699 --> 00:22:33.060
Do you have multiple servers?

00:22:34.579 --> 00:22:37.219
I'm a huge fan of ShinyApps.io.

00:22:38.420 --> 00:22:42.579
So I have probably 10 client apps on ShinyApps.

00:22:44.739 --> 00:22:50.500
We've been totally good with just the, I think, $100 a month package that offers a certain

00:22:50.500 --> 00:22:52.660
number of hours in authentication.

00:22:52.660 --> 00:22:57.780
So I just, it's a matter of literally inviting someone via their work email address to the

00:22:57.780 --> 00:22:58.339
Shiny app.

00:22:58.900 --> 00:23:06.020
And we've had as much as, like, probably 30 people on ShinyApps and totally handled everything

00:23:06.020 --> 00:23:08.180
great for one app.

00:23:08.180 --> 00:23:11.780
And then another, some other client apps where there's only a few people, but they're power

00:23:11.780 --> 00:23:13.540
users and they're constantly using it.

00:23:13.540 --> 00:23:18.260
So ShinyApps has been, I haven't needed ArcConnect yet, but we do help clients that have their

00:23:18.260 --> 00:23:19.540
own ArcConnect internally.

00:23:20.739 --> 00:23:22.979
And then we just work with their internal ArcConnect team.

00:23:25.540 --> 00:23:26.979
Nice, thank you.

00:23:26.979 --> 00:23:32.579
I see another anonymous question was, what was your biggest win for a client that was

00:23:32.579 --> 00:23:33.699
data science driven?

00:23:36.739 --> 00:23:40.979
Win as in, like, I'm assuming, I mean, like, great, like a good success story.

00:23:42.900 --> 00:23:46.339
So that's a good question.

00:23:48.579 --> 00:23:55.459
I think that there's been a couple, one of them, it doesn't seem as, it doesn't sound

00:23:55.459 --> 00:24:02.020
super cool, but there was a small pharma company that was analyzing their clinical trial data

00:24:02.020 --> 00:24:05.300
and trying to understand what's called protocol deviations.

00:24:05.300 --> 00:24:13.459
So when a patient either disqualifies or doesn't get enrolled and something went wrong in the

00:24:13.459 --> 00:24:18.900
trial, whether it's like wrong inclusion criteria, like they had the wrong cholesterol

00:24:18.900 --> 00:24:23.300
measurement and they were accepted or something like that, they were doing all this super

00:24:23.300 --> 00:24:28.339
manually generating reports in Excel and putting together a PowerPoint weekly.

00:24:28.339 --> 00:24:32.260
And it probably took like 20 hours of multiple people's time.

00:24:33.459 --> 00:24:37.459
We made a ShinyApp and turned that into like pretty much no time at all.

00:24:37.459 --> 00:24:41.619
They sent us the data, it was updated monthly and they were able to take that to, you know,

00:24:41.619 --> 00:24:47.300
senior management and clinical trial managers and make decisions based off that data super

00:24:47.300 --> 00:24:51.780
quickly and understand which clinical trial sites were having problems, what were the

00:24:51.780 --> 00:24:52.660
biggest problems.

00:24:52.660 --> 00:24:58.260
And that is just, I think, huge versus like hand crafting all these charts over and over

00:24:58.260 --> 00:25:00.660
and over and wrangling the data.

00:25:00.660 --> 00:25:06.500
So we've had a lot of wins just from moving someone off Excel into a reproducible like

00:25:06.500 --> 00:25:09.619
R pipeline and then displaying all the results in Shiny.

00:25:11.619 --> 00:25:15.859
Another similar one I wanted to mention is another pharmaceutical company.

00:25:17.619 --> 00:25:20.979
In drug manufacturing, there are a lot of things that can go wrong.

00:25:20.979 --> 00:25:28.180
And when there's a contaminant or something in a batch, it can basically, it's millions

00:25:28.180 --> 00:25:34.579
and millions of dollars of company loss because they shut down manufacturing completely until

00:25:34.579 --> 00:25:35.619
they identify the problem.

00:25:36.260 --> 00:25:41.300
And that involves going up and downstream of these different kind of drug products.

00:25:41.300 --> 00:25:45.060
And, you know, two of these molecules make something and then it goes into something

00:25:45.060 --> 00:25:45.859
else and something else.

00:25:45.859 --> 00:25:53.459
So it was taking a team of like five to 10 people, sometimes six months to identify the

00:25:53.459 --> 00:25:56.260
problem, meaning you're not manufacturing drugs at that time.

00:25:58.020 --> 00:26:03.780
We built a ShinyApp that built out a kind of D3 directed graph.

00:26:03.859 --> 00:26:11.859
So it enabled one person to go and type in the drug compound, see everything up and downstream.

00:26:11.859 --> 00:26:16.660
And it took one person now maybe a week or several days to identify that problem.

00:26:16.660 --> 00:26:19.699
So that's, you know, that's an instance where you could say this is literally millions of

00:26:19.699 --> 00:26:23.380
dollars of savings from a ShinyApp, right?

00:26:23.380 --> 00:26:24.420
So that to me is cool.

00:26:24.420 --> 00:26:28.660
And that just shows the power of R and the ability to really streamline manual

00:26:30.180 --> 00:26:31.060
processes like that.

00:26:31.380 --> 00:26:32.819
It's an amazing example.

00:26:33.939 --> 00:26:36.819
I'm just writing that, writing that time stamp down.

00:26:38.020 --> 00:26:38.579
That's great.

00:26:39.219 --> 00:26:45.060
So I see there's a few others on Slido, but I see Niels, you asked a question in the chat

00:26:45.060 --> 00:26:45.540
too.

00:26:45.540 --> 00:26:46.420
Do you want to jump in?

00:26:50.739 --> 00:26:53.619
I can ask the question if you want to add context.

00:26:54.500 --> 00:26:57.859
How do you deal with maintenance of projects?

00:26:57.859 --> 00:27:00.020
How much is included or not included?

00:27:02.020 --> 00:27:04.099
Yep, that's a good one too.

00:27:04.099 --> 00:27:08.819
Typically, we'll have a support rate depending on the person and the skills needed.

00:27:10.339 --> 00:27:14.260
And it's, we'll either do like a retainer, like you get 10 hours a week, five hours a

00:27:14.260 --> 00:27:15.060
week of support.

00:27:15.060 --> 00:27:16.819
And that's an average.

00:27:17.939 --> 00:27:20.020
And then they'll bill hourly and what they actually do.

00:27:21.219 --> 00:27:25.060
Or you just agree that it's going to be an average of certain number of hours per month.

00:27:25.060 --> 00:27:28.739
And some months is more or less, and you just, they just pay that fixed amount every month.

00:27:31.060 --> 00:27:35.699
Typically, I think hourly works best for maintenance, just in case things go really

00:27:35.699 --> 00:27:36.099
haywire.

00:27:36.099 --> 00:27:42.500
But the biggest thing is agreeing on a reasonable SLA, so service level agreement.

00:27:42.500 --> 00:27:45.380
So do you need someone within like two hours?

00:27:45.380 --> 00:27:47.380
That's, we'll charge a lot more for that.

00:27:48.500 --> 00:27:51.540
Is it within 72 hours, three days, 48 hours?

00:27:52.500 --> 00:27:55.300
You know, that's, that's usually what we try to go for.

00:27:55.300 --> 00:28:01.140
Because I try to, I try to work with projects and clients where nothing is an actual emergency.

00:28:02.020 --> 00:28:07.140
Like I'm not a brain surgeon and, you know, data's fun, but there's usually nothing that's

00:28:07.140 --> 00:28:08.180
life-threatening.

00:28:08.180 --> 00:28:13.540
So making sure they have reasonable SLAs and not expected to like jump out of bed at 2

00:28:13.540 --> 00:28:13.859
a.m.

00:28:13.859 --> 00:28:16.020
to fix something is good for your sanity.

00:28:18.500 --> 00:28:19.140
Absolutely.

00:28:20.979 --> 00:28:24.579
Caitlin, I see you asked a great question in the chat too, if you want to jump in next.

00:28:26.260 --> 00:28:31.380
All right, so I was just wondering if you could touch a little bit on your progression

00:28:31.380 --> 00:28:33.060
through your data science roles.

00:28:33.060 --> 00:28:37.140
Like I was just looking at your LinkedIn and I saw you're an analyst, data scientist,

00:28:38.180 --> 00:28:43.699
CDO, VP, and I was just wondering how did you kind of know when it was your time to

00:28:43.699 --> 00:28:44.579
switch roles or?

00:28:46.339 --> 00:28:47.699
Yeah, yeah, that's a great question.

00:28:48.579 --> 00:28:53.540
So my first job, I was learning a ton and just felt super way in over my head and I

00:28:53.540 --> 00:28:56.500
was like a bioinformatics scientist or something.

00:28:57.859 --> 00:29:01.859
And I just, I stayed there for about five years, got a few promotions to like start

00:29:01.859 --> 00:29:04.979
helping with the sales of what we were doing.

00:29:05.780 --> 00:29:09.459
So that was good, but eventually just wanted to try something else.

00:29:10.579 --> 00:29:13.459
Got basically a similar role.

00:29:13.459 --> 00:29:21.540
It was kind of a sort of parallel move and I had a lot less responsibility, but it was

00:29:21.540 --> 00:29:23.540
a different, completely different industry.

00:29:23.540 --> 00:29:27.219
And I was learning instead of, I wasn't in bioinformatics, I'm more biotech.

00:29:27.219 --> 00:29:34.180
I was learning about distributed software and databases, but I felt like I wasn't being

00:29:34.180 --> 00:29:38.579
pushed and I didn't really, I wasn't learning much beyond about the distributed systems

00:29:38.579 --> 00:29:41.060
in terms of my data science skills.

00:29:41.060 --> 00:29:43.619
They were kind of stalling.

00:29:44.180 --> 00:29:50.020
Like I found myself supporting Salesforce and helping sales guys do very menial tasks

00:29:50.579 --> 00:29:51.300
which is great.

00:29:51.300 --> 00:29:55.699
Like I did get to, I started using Tableau there and I got more experience working with

00:29:55.699 --> 00:29:56.420
business leaders.

00:29:56.979 --> 00:30:02.500
And then I realized, okay, I want to try managing and having like a big role at a startup.

00:30:02.500 --> 00:30:04.260
And so that's what I did next.

00:30:04.260 --> 00:30:09.939
I found a role at a telecom company and was really brought in to like transform their

00:30:09.939 --> 00:30:13.380
entire consulting business into a data products company.

00:30:13.380 --> 00:30:19.380
And this is a company that was operating very much as a consultancy, but they had really,

00:30:19.380 --> 00:30:22.099
really valuable data and a very good use case.

00:30:22.099 --> 00:30:29.219
They were helping telecom providers understand when and why people switched.

00:30:29.219 --> 00:30:33.780
So back in the day, you know, you were always, you were going to T-Mobile, Verizon or Sprint

00:30:33.780 --> 00:30:37.060
and you didn't, everyone had a phone number eventually.

00:30:37.060 --> 00:30:41.219
And then it became a poaching game of like Verizon trying to steal T-Mobile's customers

00:30:41.219 --> 00:30:41.859
and vice versa.

00:30:41.859 --> 00:30:45.540
So they had all that data because you take your phone number with you when you switch.

00:30:46.420 --> 00:30:47.540
They had your zip code.

00:30:47.540 --> 00:30:49.219
They had, you know, a lot of different things.

00:30:49.780 --> 00:30:52.819
So I saw that and I was like, well, that's valuable.

00:30:52.819 --> 00:30:57.699
And we, I could see why, you know, Verizon would want to know where high value T-Mobile

00:30:57.699 --> 00:30:59.699
customers are located in California.

00:31:00.900 --> 00:31:05.540
So anyway, that's a long way of saying I saw the value in the data.

00:31:05.540 --> 00:31:07.859
I felt like I could really make a difference there.

00:31:07.859 --> 00:31:13.619
People were like copy pasting SQL scripts and not saving anything they were doing and

00:31:13.619 --> 00:31:18.500
fat fingers in Excel and not able to reproduce past reports that we had sent to, you know,

00:31:18.579 --> 00:31:20.020
our biggest paying customer.

00:31:21.859 --> 00:31:27.060
So yeah, I was brought into it and I helped hire people and I worked my ass off, but it

00:31:27.060 --> 00:31:28.900
was like a really good, great experience.

00:31:28.900 --> 00:31:31.699
And then I started to get a little burnt out.

00:31:31.699 --> 00:31:36.500
And I think that's when I decided to go back to healthcare and a big company.

00:31:37.140 --> 00:31:42.099
I kind of played the, I was a data scientist and just took my time to learn a bunch of

00:31:42.099 --> 00:31:42.500
things.

00:31:43.699 --> 00:31:45.540
And that's when I started consulting on the side.

00:31:46.180 --> 00:31:47.939
It became much too much.

00:31:47.939 --> 00:31:50.660
I was working at night and weekends and my full-time job.

00:31:50.660 --> 00:31:51.699
And I was like, it's time.

00:31:51.699 --> 00:31:53.380
I'm just going to talk to my boss.

00:31:53.380 --> 00:31:58.979
Luckily, my boss was very understanding and he, we brought them on as a client.

00:31:58.979 --> 00:32:04.420
So now, you know, we were able to have Biogen as a client and these different companies

00:32:04.420 --> 00:32:05.219
that I worked for.

00:32:05.219 --> 00:32:11.140
So I think it's when you feel like your skills are stalling or you feel like you're not

00:32:11.140 --> 00:32:11.939
being challenged.

00:32:11.939 --> 00:32:17.060
I definitely felt like, okay, it's time to make a move and use everything I learned to

00:32:17.060 --> 00:32:18.900
like go make a difference somewhere.

00:32:20.979 --> 00:32:22.020
That's really interesting.

00:32:22.020 --> 00:32:22.819
Thank you.

00:32:22.819 --> 00:32:23.319
Yeah.

00:32:24.979 --> 00:32:25.380
Thank you.

00:32:25.380 --> 00:32:26.180
That's really helpful.

00:32:27.619 --> 00:32:30.900
Lisa, I know you put a question into the chat too, if you want to go next.

00:32:33.380 --> 00:32:34.020
Sure.

00:32:34.020 --> 00:32:35.300
Hopefully you can hear me okay.

00:32:36.020 --> 00:32:41.540
So it, yeah, it looks like a lot of, or from what you described, a lot of your big wins

00:32:41.540 --> 00:32:49.619
are from, you know, maybe complex, maybe involving shiny apps, data summaries and visualizations.

00:32:49.619 --> 00:32:55.380
And I'm just wondering, you know, how often you find yourself doing that type of work.

00:32:55.380 --> 00:33:03.540
And I'm really curious about if, you know, do your clients go in thinking like, oh, they're

00:33:04.180 --> 00:33:10.260
going to make us a complex data viz, or do they go in thinking we need AI and machine

00:33:10.260 --> 00:33:16.739
learning and you are kind of like, you know, pulling them back a little.

00:33:18.979 --> 00:33:20.020
Yes, yes, yes.

00:33:20.020 --> 00:33:25.380
So like everything, basically I would, I always tell people, I would say we really only do

00:33:26.180 --> 00:33:29.540
machine learning, statistical modeling, maybe 20% of the time.

00:33:30.180 --> 00:33:38.660
A lot of work we do is, like you said, data summaries, visualization, automating manual

00:33:38.660 --> 00:33:43.699
processes and moving them out of Excel, a lot of shiny app, shiny development work.

00:33:45.859 --> 00:33:48.579
I could give an example about the Department of Defense.

00:33:48.579 --> 00:33:51.780
They had budget for a big AI machine learning effort.

00:33:53.140 --> 00:33:56.020
We did actually end up doing some pretty cool machine learning for them.

00:33:56.180 --> 00:34:00.180
But like you said, a lot of companies think they need machine learning or AI, and they

00:34:00.180 --> 00:34:03.219
really don't, like they just need some summary statistics.

00:34:03.939 --> 00:34:07.219
And we can talk them off the ledge with that by usually just showing them what can be done.

00:34:07.219 --> 00:34:10.580
And then they see it and they're happy.

00:34:10.580 --> 00:34:13.780
They realize, okay, maybe that was, maybe that's down the road.

00:34:14.979 --> 00:34:18.580
But for the Department of Defense, they had an inventory problem.

00:34:18.580 --> 00:34:25.300
So every time anything is purchased in the army, anything from back to front,

00:34:25.300 --> 00:34:29.699
anything from batteries to laptops to Apache helicopter parts, it's all entered into a

00:34:29.699 --> 00:34:30.340
database.

00:34:30.340 --> 00:34:34.419
And it's entered pretty much manually on the field from a laptop.

00:34:34.419 --> 00:34:39.939
So there's a lot of typos and fat fingering, zeros that are O's, ones that are L's.

00:34:41.780 --> 00:34:46.419
And we're talking like 1.2, I want to say it was billion records or something.

00:34:47.300 --> 00:34:52.580
So there's no easy way to go in and just fuzzy match or deduplicate.

00:34:52.580 --> 00:34:57.219
So if the army doesn't know what's readily on hand in the inventory, how can they be

00:34:59.060 --> 00:35:01.459
ready for certain situations?

00:35:01.459 --> 00:35:07.060
So we were brought in to do that, did some really cool, we used some genetic algorithms.

00:35:07.060 --> 00:35:11.379
I don't remember off the top of my head exactly which ones, but ways of comparing different

00:35:11.379 --> 00:35:18.979
fields and then quantifying things like the keyboard distance from different keys, common

00:35:18.979 --> 00:35:19.540
typos.

00:35:20.020 --> 00:35:25.540
And then using Levenstein distance for fuzzy matching and combining all these things into a

00:35:25.540 --> 00:35:29.860
very custom machine learning solution for them.

00:35:29.860 --> 00:35:31.939
And then using a shiny app to expose the results.

00:35:31.939 --> 00:35:38.020
So we found a whole bunch of items that were clustered together because they were very

00:35:38.020 --> 00:35:40.020
similar, but they were duplicates.

00:35:40.020 --> 00:35:43.219
And so then we worked on scaling that with them and helping them find all those.

00:35:44.739 --> 00:35:48.979
Now the AI part, we kept explaining them that's way off in the distance, right?

00:35:49.540 --> 00:35:52.739
You have to do the machine learning first, have a human in the loop.

00:35:53.699 --> 00:35:54.899
That's what the shiny app did.

00:35:54.899 --> 00:36:00.020
It helped us then visualize the results and then agree with them and say, this is right,

00:36:00.020 --> 00:36:00.659
this is not.

00:36:01.300 --> 00:36:06.260
And that we kept explaining to them like that builds up your training set.

00:36:06.260 --> 00:36:09.860
So have someone come in, there is manual work involved.

00:36:09.860 --> 00:36:14.580
This isn't a magic button where a robot comes in and just does it all.

00:36:14.580 --> 00:36:19.139
So I think it's the hump between machine learning to AI that's really complicated because

00:36:19.139 --> 00:36:22.260
there's no way you turn on a switch and just let the machine automatically do this stuff,

00:36:22.260 --> 00:36:26.580
especially if it's very important, let's say healthcare related data.

00:36:27.939 --> 00:36:29.780
So yeah, you're totally right.

00:36:29.780 --> 00:36:31.139
And we talked them off the ledge.

00:36:31.139 --> 00:36:34.500
And I wouldn't say that we've ever done artificial intelligence yet at this point.

00:36:34.500 --> 00:36:38.340
We've done a lot of machine learning, but getting to the AI part is a lot of, I think,

00:36:38.340 --> 00:36:44.580
human involved work to get there until you feel comfortable enough turning that switch

00:36:44.580 --> 00:36:46.899
and letting the machines take over.

00:36:49.300 --> 00:36:49.860
Thank you.

00:36:49.860 --> 00:36:51.060
That's a really cool example.

00:36:53.060 --> 00:36:54.100
Let me see.

00:36:54.100 --> 00:36:57.540
There's a few other questions that were on Slido earlier I wanted to make sure I get

00:36:57.540 --> 00:36:58.100
to as well.

00:36:58.100 --> 00:37:00.820
And both were around dealing with sensitive data.

00:37:01.939 --> 00:37:05.939
Do you have experience working with clients who manage sensitive health data?

00:37:05.939 --> 00:37:09.780
Are there HIPAA compliant blueprints out there for hosting shiny apps?

00:37:11.060 --> 00:37:12.739
Oh, very good question.

00:37:12.739 --> 00:37:13.620
We have a lot.

00:37:13.620 --> 00:37:18.500
And we've struggled in the past with, you know, especially with, you know,

00:37:18.500 --> 00:37:23.939
especially with the drug manufacturing work we're doing.

00:37:23.939 --> 00:37:30.419
I had to do some research on making sure it was all, I can't remember the word now.

00:37:30.419 --> 00:37:35.780
It's not, well, FDA, you know, there's FDA regulations and there's all kinds of things

00:37:35.780 --> 00:37:36.500
you have to comply with.

00:37:36.500 --> 00:37:41.139
But for the most part, we haven't, you know, run into any issues where we just literally

00:37:41.139 --> 00:37:42.100
can't do something.

00:37:42.580 --> 00:37:52.100
People are typically trustworthy now or trusting of AWS and they have HIPAA compliant clusters.

00:37:52.100 --> 00:37:53.860
There's also a GovCloud.

00:37:54.739 --> 00:37:56.100
So we use that for the DoD.

00:37:56.739 --> 00:37:59.139
Luckily, the data we're working with, nothing was classified.

00:37:59.139 --> 00:38:00.580
So that helped.

00:38:00.580 --> 00:38:02.179
I didn't need like security clearance.

00:38:04.020 --> 00:38:08.739
But yeah, it's, I think there's a lot of stuff out there now to support it.

00:38:08.739 --> 00:38:12.100
R can be validated in a clinical environment as well.

00:38:12.100 --> 00:38:16.419
And usually it involves just writing proper unit tests and making sure things are reproducible.

00:38:17.939 --> 00:38:22.340
So we've had the discussions, but it's never been like a showstopper.

00:38:22.340 --> 00:38:25.300
And usually it comes down to, well, we need everything in our cloud.

00:38:25.300 --> 00:38:28.100
So they have their own RConnect and it's behind their VPN and firewall.

00:38:28.820 --> 00:38:32.580
But yeah, the AWS HIPAA clusters we've used.

00:38:32.580 --> 00:38:34.820
I actually don't know though with Shining Apps.

00:38:35.780 --> 00:38:40.739
I haven't run into that situation yet where it's been a problem, but I'd be curious.

00:38:40.739 --> 00:38:43.060
Like definitely feel free to follow up with me after too.

00:38:44.419 --> 00:38:48.260
I think Rachel, you might share my Twitter or something at the end so people can reach out.

00:38:49.300 --> 00:38:50.020
Definitely.

00:38:50.020 --> 00:38:50.260
Yeah.

00:38:50.260 --> 00:38:54.979
And I think the other question touches upon this too, because it was asking around Shining Apps

00:38:54.979 --> 00:38:55.620
IO.

00:38:55.620 --> 00:38:57.459
Isn't that hosted by RStudio?

00:38:58.340 --> 00:38:59.780
So what about the sensitive data?

00:38:59.780 --> 00:39:02.580
But I think you just answered as well.

00:39:03.540 --> 00:39:03.860
Yeah.

00:39:03.860 --> 00:39:07.699
I typically just tell clients like, look, the AWS is going to be more secure probably than

00:39:08.820 --> 00:39:11.060
what you've got on site, but it really depends.

00:39:12.580 --> 00:39:17.860
So I think people are becoming more and more trusting of the cloud.

00:39:17.860 --> 00:39:18.419
So that helps.

00:39:21.060 --> 00:39:21.540
Thank you.

00:39:22.899 --> 00:39:27.060
Javier, I see you put a question to the chat a bit ago as well, if you want to jump in.

00:39:29.699 --> 00:39:30.260
Yeah, thanks.

00:39:30.419 --> 00:39:36.340
It touches on ShinyApps.io as well, just about package management.

00:39:39.379 --> 00:39:47.939
Are you building project-specific packages or packages that contain modules or functions

00:39:47.939 --> 00:39:49.139
that you're reusing a lot?

00:39:49.139 --> 00:39:54.580
And if so, how are you deploying that to Shiny Apps?

00:39:55.139 --> 00:39:55.639
Yeah.

00:39:56.500 --> 00:40:02.659
So actually, most recently, we started using Gollum, which makes production-grade Shiny

00:40:02.659 --> 00:40:06.659
applications and gives you a whole bunch of stuff like testing and documentation.

00:40:07.939 --> 00:40:09.620
But we didn't have a problem.

00:40:09.620 --> 00:40:15.300
We built our own package that did some custom D3 visualization for a pharma company.

00:40:16.979 --> 00:40:21.379
And we didn't deploy it on Shiny Apps, but they deployed it internally to our Connect

00:40:21.379 --> 00:40:23.540
server, and there were no problems there.

00:40:23.540 --> 00:40:28.659
So I haven't had any issues yet, or I haven't deployed my own package to Shiny Apps.

00:40:30.580 --> 00:40:36.580
But using Gollum, we had no problems deploying our own package to our Connect.

00:40:36.580 --> 00:40:38.580
So I don't know if that answers it, but...

00:40:38.580 --> 00:40:39.300
It does, yeah.

00:40:39.300 --> 00:40:40.260
That's awesome.

00:40:40.260 --> 00:40:40.979
Thanks.

00:40:40.979 --> 00:40:41.479
Yeah.

00:40:44.500 --> 00:40:45.379
Awesome.

00:40:45.379 --> 00:40:48.340
Tiffany, I see you just put a question in the chat, if you want to jump in.

00:40:53.860 --> 00:40:54.360
Hi.

00:40:55.300 --> 00:41:00.260
Yeah, I just was wondering if you do most of your work remotely, or if you ever get

00:41:00.260 --> 00:41:02.100
to visit the companies that you work with.

00:41:02.739 --> 00:41:08.979
And if you get to visit, do you find there's a lot of value seeing where that data is generated?

00:41:10.179 --> 00:41:17.780
For example, if you go visit a lab and you get to witness how the scientists are entering

00:41:17.780 --> 00:41:25.300
their data, maybe that gives you some greater insights on how to generate your apps to capture

00:41:25.300 --> 00:41:26.659
that and help them.

00:41:26.659 --> 00:41:27.459
Yeah, yeah.

00:41:27.459 --> 00:41:28.500
That's an awesome question.

00:41:29.620 --> 00:41:32.020
Well, during a pandemic, of course, it was all remote.

00:41:32.020 --> 00:41:34.179
But yeah, we're a remote-based company.

00:41:35.060 --> 00:41:39.699
However, yeah, I used to go into client sites probably at least a few times a week.

00:41:41.379 --> 00:41:45.219
And oftentimes, yeah, I do think it's helpful.

00:41:45.860 --> 00:41:50.979
Not only can you understand how the data is being generated sometimes, but understanding

00:41:50.979 --> 00:41:56.979
the politics of situations too, where people work, how they work together, how often they're

00:41:56.979 --> 00:41:57.780
talking.

00:41:57.780 --> 00:42:01.780
There's just a lot of things you can pick up on when you are on site.

00:42:03.379 --> 00:42:06.340
And of course, whiteboarding things is really nice.

00:42:06.340 --> 00:42:13.540
But one example I can think of that was pretty cool was we work for a health care devices

00:42:13.540 --> 00:42:15.300
company that creates the...

00:42:15.300 --> 00:42:18.659
They manufacture the rapid blood testing kits in hospitals.

00:42:18.659 --> 00:42:25.300
So if you're at a hospital, hopefully you're not, you get your blood drawn and they have

00:42:25.300 --> 00:42:26.340
the results very rapidly.

00:42:26.340 --> 00:42:29.540
That's the company that we do work for.

00:42:29.540 --> 00:42:35.620
And their problem was that they had all these faulty devices going out into the field at

00:42:35.620 --> 00:42:38.580
times, make things happen with hardware fails.

00:42:39.379 --> 00:42:42.179
But there's a ton of sensor data coming off of those machines.

00:42:43.379 --> 00:42:49.780
And so we were brought in to do some anomaly detection, identify some spikes in particular

00:42:49.780 --> 00:42:55.620
proteins or problems before that hardware, that blood testing machine gets out into the

00:42:55.620 --> 00:42:57.540
fields at the various hospitals.

00:42:57.540 --> 00:43:04.820
And I got to tour that lab and it was a massive place with just all these machines.

00:43:05.139 --> 00:43:10.100
All these machines and they show me where the data's coming off of and how it gets put

00:43:10.100 --> 00:43:11.060
into a database.

00:43:11.060 --> 00:43:15.699
And I think just having that contextual knowledge and meeting with the people you're working

00:43:15.699 --> 00:43:16.739
with is invaluable.

00:43:16.739 --> 00:43:21.620
And I was definitely a person that did not enjoy going to an office every single day,

00:43:21.620 --> 00:43:26.100
but I really loved being able to go to different client sites a few times a week.

00:43:26.979 --> 00:43:29.139
So I do miss it after this pandemic.

00:43:29.139 --> 00:43:33.699
Now I think I'll appreciate it even more, but yeah, it's super valuable.

00:43:34.820 --> 00:43:37.699
One of our clients is opening a drug manufacturing plant in Switzerland.

00:43:37.699 --> 00:43:39.139
So of course, I'm trying to go there.

00:43:43.060 --> 00:43:43.780
That's great.

00:43:43.780 --> 00:43:45.939
I love how relaxed Porkchop is back there.

00:43:47.219 --> 00:43:48.659
He doesn't earn his keeper up here.

00:43:48.659 --> 00:43:49.780
He needs to work a little harder.

00:43:51.540 --> 00:43:52.899
He's our chief security officer.

00:43:55.060 --> 00:44:00.340
I was curious, Tanya, what has been the hardest thing about starting your own company?

00:44:01.060 --> 00:44:02.820
Oh, hardest thing.

00:44:04.820 --> 00:44:06.260
Well, there's been challenges.

00:44:06.260 --> 00:44:11.379
The first, when I gave my two weeks, there's obviously a huge panic.

00:44:11.379 --> 00:44:13.620
Like, wow, the checks are going to stop coming in.

00:44:14.500 --> 00:44:15.620
Yeah, get a job, Porkchop.

00:44:16.979 --> 00:44:21.780
And there's that panic that sets in like, OK, this is really all up to me now.

00:44:22.899 --> 00:44:24.979
Now, if you have a spouse, of course, that helps.

00:44:24.979 --> 00:44:29.379
Like I had health insurance because I was able to go on my wife's insurance.

00:44:30.340 --> 00:44:32.659
And obviously, that helps.

00:44:32.659 --> 00:44:35.139
And I saved a bunch of money before making the leaps.

00:44:35.139 --> 00:44:36.580
I had an emergency fund and all that.

00:44:36.580 --> 00:44:37.939
But that's scary.

00:44:38.580 --> 00:44:41.300
I would say that's the hardest part is really just making the leap.

00:44:41.300 --> 00:44:44.500
But two weeks into it, I never looked back.

00:44:44.500 --> 00:44:45.540
I was like, this is it.

00:44:45.540 --> 00:44:46.260
This is awesome.

00:44:46.260 --> 00:44:47.300
It's working out.

00:44:48.580 --> 00:44:49.860
And you just got to keep going.

00:44:49.860 --> 00:44:52.580
And it's nice to know it's all kind of on you.

00:44:52.580 --> 00:44:55.459
And you can't really blame other people now if things fail.

00:44:55.459 --> 00:44:59.459
Or there's always people involved.

00:44:59.459 --> 00:45:03.699
But it's nice to know that you're kind of in charge of if you want to make more money

00:45:03.699 --> 00:45:05.300
one year, you work a lot more.

00:45:05.300 --> 00:45:08.179
If you don't care and you're OK, then that's fine.

00:45:08.179 --> 00:45:12.020
And I'm definitely a person, I'm enjoying work-life balance a lot more now.

00:45:12.020 --> 00:45:13.699
So I try not to overload myself.

00:45:15.219 --> 00:45:17.780
But in consulting, it's also waves.

00:45:17.780 --> 00:45:21.939
It totally always happens that suddenly we have like 10 leads come in.

00:45:22.020 --> 00:45:25.780
And sometimes I have a hard time saying no because it's such an interesting project.

00:45:25.780 --> 00:45:27.060
And I want to work with these people.

00:45:27.939 --> 00:45:31.219
So I'll pull in more consultants to help if I need to.

00:45:32.179 --> 00:45:32.899
So that stuff.

00:45:32.899 --> 00:45:37.939
And then also not having stuff like this, which is why I'm so glad that you do these

00:45:37.939 --> 00:45:38.439
Hangouts.

00:45:39.300 --> 00:45:42.899
Not interact with people every day in an office, obviously.

00:45:44.179 --> 00:45:46.260
Sometimes it's nice to just talk to other data nerds.

00:45:46.260 --> 00:45:50.659
So I have some friends that I talk to that also consult and will kind of commiserate

00:45:50.659 --> 00:45:52.179
about problems or ask for advice.

00:45:52.979 --> 00:45:57.139
And the other thing I did was I started a Slack community of data scientists.

00:45:57.139 --> 00:46:01.379
So when I went out on my own, I knew I wanted to keep in touch with all these awesome people

00:46:01.379 --> 00:46:07.860
that I met throughout the years, whether at conferences or at jobs, college friends even.

00:46:07.860 --> 00:46:10.419
And so I invited them to a Slack community.

00:46:10.419 --> 00:46:12.340
It's kind of grown organically over the years.

00:46:13.379 --> 00:46:14.739
It's called Friendly Tech Space.

00:46:14.739 --> 00:46:17.219
And you can feel free to message me if you'd like an invite.

