I'd love to hear from someone else how you've evangelized R,

00:50:08.179 --> 00:50:10.899
what you've done being the solo R person.

00:50:15.939 --> 00:50:17.540
No, go ahead, Lisa, please.

00:50:18.820 --> 00:50:21.060
I mean, I'm very new to my job.

00:50:21.060 --> 00:50:29.060
But I think there's still a sense that R is this statistical programming language,

00:50:29.060 --> 00:50:29.860
which it is.

00:50:30.580 --> 00:50:38.340
But I think the way to pull things in is actually with more like the parameterized reporting.

00:50:38.340 --> 00:50:45.219
And eventually stuff like shiny, I need a lot more tooling set up to be able to do that nicely.

00:50:45.219 --> 00:50:49.939
But I don't think, at least not people in my organization, they don't think like,

00:50:49.939 --> 00:50:53.139
oh, R is great for making reproducible reports.

00:50:53.139 --> 00:50:56.100
And I'm like, no, it's really good at that.

00:50:59.139 --> 00:51:02.100
So just showing off some of that stuff that people don't know about.

00:51:03.060 --> 00:51:05.780
Yeah, and I think we've taught a lot of R, too.

00:51:05.780 --> 00:51:10.659
And one thing that makes people kind of get it is we do this exercise where you give half

00:51:10.659 --> 00:51:15.620
the class a task to do in Excel, and half the class does it in R.

00:51:15.620 --> 00:51:17.699
And then we just change a parameter.

00:51:17.699 --> 00:51:21.860
We say, OK, now do the same thing, but for this baseball player instead of this one.

00:51:21.860 --> 00:51:23.860
And the R side is done in like two seconds.

00:51:23.860 --> 00:51:26.260
And they just change one thing at the top of the script.

00:51:26.260 --> 00:51:31.060
The Excel people are like going to get the data again, and having to wrangle it and do

00:51:31.060 --> 00:51:31.459
things.

00:51:31.459 --> 00:51:36.899
And it really gets people, I think, to like, oh, I get what scripting is now and why it's

00:51:37.620 --> 00:51:38.979
fast and reproducible.

00:51:41.860 --> 00:51:42.899
That's such a good idea.

00:51:44.659 --> 00:51:46.340
Javier, I know you were about to jump in, too.

00:51:46.899 --> 00:51:50.020
No, I mean, Lisa kind of took the words out of my mouth.

00:51:50.020 --> 00:51:51.540
So same kind of thing.

00:51:52.979 --> 00:51:56.100
I partner a lot with, I mean, I used to be in finance.

00:51:56.739 --> 00:52:01.620
So I end up partnering often with our finance teams.

00:52:01.620 --> 00:52:09.139
And they generally see the value, let's say, right away because they understand the limitations

00:52:09.139 --> 00:52:12.820
of Excel or something like Excel that they might be using.

00:52:14.500 --> 00:52:22.820
