00:57:13.239 --> 00:57:16.199
I must be terrible and not a very good data scientist.

00:57:16.199 --> 00:57:19.639
Um, so have you ever dealt with imposter syndrome and.

00:57:20.280 --> 00:57:21.800
You know, what did that feel like for you?

00:57:22.360 --> 00:57:26.439
I, yeah, I think if anyone has an experience that they're doing something wrong,

00:57:27.639 --> 00:57:31.639
like, uh, cause I mean, there's so many talented people out there and like,

00:57:31.639 --> 00:57:35.080
you know, at my first job, especially, I, like I said, it was all like PhD

00:57:35.719 --> 00:57:37.719
level statisticians from Cornell.

00:57:37.719 --> 00:57:43.399
And, um, I just, you know, I'd be in three hour long conversations about them debating

00:57:43.399 --> 00:57:47.479
and use of a various certain prior for Bayesian algorithm.

00:57:47.800 --> 00:57:50.439
Anyway, I, um, yeah, of course.

00:57:50.439 --> 00:57:54.600
And I think, uh, what you have to realize too, is what people are putting out there

00:57:54.600 --> 00:57:55.479
and people on Twitter.

00:57:55.479 --> 00:58:00.679
That's, you know, oftentimes they're focused very much on one thing or it's their entire

00:58:00.679 --> 00:58:02.600
career and their job is based around it.

00:58:02.600 --> 00:58:08.600
And, um, I've learned, like, I don't have to be the best to any one thing, uh, but I

00:58:08.600 --> 00:58:10.040
can focus on what I am good at.

00:58:10.040 --> 00:58:15.879
And if that's, uh, helping, you know, with the technical communication between the business

00:58:15.879 --> 00:58:18.840
and the tech people, then I'll focus there.

00:58:18.840 --> 00:58:20.840
Like I'm, I don't have to be the best coder.

00:58:20.840 --> 00:58:25.479
I can bring in someone that I know is a D3 wizard, or I can bring in someone that I know

00:58:25.479 --> 00:58:27.719
is great at optimizing code.

00:58:27.719 --> 00:58:30.840
Um, I've always felt like I know enough to be dangerous.

00:58:30.840 --> 00:58:34.280
Um, but yeah, I think everyone deals with it.

00:58:34.280 --> 00:58:38.760
And at the end of the day, you know, there's way too much to know to absolutely feel like

00:58:38.760 --> 00:58:40.919
you're an expert at almost anything.

00:58:41.879 --> 00:58:47.239
Like I, when I do time series forecasting for a client, it's, I use packages that are

00:58:47.239 --> 00:58:47.800
available.

00:58:47.800 --> 00:58:54.600
I, I try to, you know, consult with, if I need to consult with a statistician that I'm

00:58:54.600 --> 00:58:56.199
one of my good friends, I trust I will.

00:58:56.760 --> 00:59:02.520
Um, but there are people that spend their entire lives, like researching just one segment

00:59:02.520 --> 00:59:03.639
of time series forecasting.

00:59:03.639 --> 00:59:04.360
Right.

00:59:04.360 --> 00:59:08.360
So, um, yeah, just keep learning and it's possible to know it all.

